{"title_page": "Bobby Cummines", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bobby Cummines\n| honorific_suffix   = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE|FRSA}}\n| image              = Bobby Cummines OBE MUniv. FRSA.gif\n| alt                = Bobby Cummines OBE MUniv. FRSA\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1951|11|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = Islington, London, United Kingdom <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randomhouse.com.au/books/robert-cummines/i-am-not-a-gangster-9780091958589.aspx|title=I Am Not A Gangster by Bobby Cummines - Books - Random House Books Australia|last=Cummines|first=Bobby|publisher=[[Random House]]|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = United Kingdom\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[UNLOCK, The National Association of Reformed Offenders | UNLOCK]], Criminal\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Robert \"Bobby\" Cummines''' {{small|[[OBE]], [[FRSA]]}} (born 23 November 1951) is an English former [[Contract killing|hitman]] who was chief executive of [[UNLOCK, The National Association of Reformed Offenders]] until March 2012. Formerly one of the United Kingdom's most notorious bank robbers, he rejects the designation of ''gangster'' as stated on \"The True Geordie Podcast\". Despite this, True Geordie titled the podcast \"The Truth About London Gangsters\". Bobby commented on the video that he would hang True Geordie from a meat hook if he called him a gangster again. <ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-con Bobby Cummines in talks to create 'criminals village' in Birmingham |url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/news/local-news/ex-con-bobby-cummines-talks-create-3934564 |work=[[Birmingham Post]] |last=Elkes|first=Neil|date=17 February 2010 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\nCummines began a criminal career at the age of 16, as Britain's youngest [[armed robber]]. He expanded into leading a group of [[contract killer]]s and [[racketeer]]s, employing extreme violence in 1970s [[North London]] with his fearsome reputation and a sawn-off double barrel shotgun named \"Kennedy\" after [[JFK]]. He also utilised a brutal method common in the underworld, filling his shotgun with salt rocks instead of shells - doing less damage but causing serious pain. Cummines claims that he did not think about anyone he killed, saying that if you did think about it then you would think of their families and guilt. He did, however, feel sorry for one death; a hostage in a routine bank heist died due to suffering a serious panic attack, where he vomited and choked on a gag.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\nCummines was sentenced to 18 years when an arms dealer (referred to as \"Ernie\" in the book){{clarify|reason=what book?|date=April 2019}} informed and told the authorities almost everything Cummines and his gang had done. Ernie worked with the police to entrap Cummines, telling him he had an [[Uzi]] sub-machine gun for sale, allowing multiple armed police to ambush and arrest him. He went to prison and within the first few months he had taken a governor hostage for being \"unreasonable\". This caused him to be designated as a class \"A\" prisoner, causing him to be frequently moved from one prison to another. In his autobiography, Cummines details how he met a broad range of people, from members of the [[Irish Republican Army]] to lavishly-living American [[Mafiosi]].{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\nCummines turned his life around in prison after a conversation with [[Charlie Richardson]] of the South London \"Torture Gang\", who urged him to become educated and earn money without hurting anyone. He began writing poetry and got into contact with [[Tony Benn]], a government minister at the time who was willing to help him and contributed a foreword to his published poems, as well as changing rules so that the aim of prisons was stated to be to \"rehabilitate and educate\" rather than the free-for-all ethos that Cummines had experienced.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\nCummines has criticised the system of high-security prisons, which places a lot of brilliant criminal minds in one location and thus enables them to teach each other tricks and connections. He has said that if he had not wanted to escape criminal life he would have utilised these techniques, such as bomb building or smuggling illicit goods.<ref name=\"Mirror\">{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/gangster-bobby-cummines-britains-youngest-3623797|title=Gangster Bobby Cummines was Britain\u2019s youngest armed robber - and ended up with an OBE - Mirror Online|last=Manger|first=Warren|date=30 May 2013|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref name = \"realcrime\">{{cite news|url=https://www.realcrimedaily.com/from-organised-crime-to-obe-how-london-gangster-bobby-cummines-became-a-model-citizen/|title=From Organised Crime to OBE: How London gangster Bobby Cummines became a model citizen|last=Matthews|first=Tanita|date=21 September 2013|work=Real Crime Daily|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref> He then studied for a degree with the [[Open University]] whilst in prison.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-38574984/youngest-armed-robber-university-changed-my-life|title=Youngest armed robber: 'University changed my life'\n|date=10 January 2017|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref><ref name = \"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2001/feb/02/crime.penal4|title=Interview: my life behind bars|date=2 February 2001|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nCummines was awarded the [[OBE]] by [[Queen Elizabeth II]] in June 2011 in recognition of his services to reformed offenders.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/jul/11/ex-prisoners-education-super-academies|title=Former bank robber dreams of academies to help prisoners go straight|last=James|first=Erwin|date=11 July 2011|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis autobiography, ''I Am Not A Gangster'', {{ISBN|9780091958589}}, was published 15 May 2014 by [[Random House]]'s [[Ebury Press]] imprint.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randomhouse.com.au/books/robert-cummines/i-am-not-a-gangster-9780091958589.aspx|title=I Am Not A Gangster by Bobby Cummines - Books - Random House Books Australia|last=Cummines|first=Bobby|publisher=[[Random House]]|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bobbycummines.com Personal website]\n*[http://www.midascharity.com MIDAS website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cummines, Bobby}}\n[[Category:British chief executives]]\n[[Category:British bank robbers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bobby Cummines\n| honorific_suffix   = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE|FRSA}}\n| image              = Bobby Cummines OBE MUniv. FRSA.gif\n| alt                = Bobby Cummines OBE MUniv. FRSA\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1951|11|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = Islington, London, United Kingdom <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.randomhouse.com.au/books/robert-cummines/i-am-not-a-gangster-9780091958589.aspx|title=I Am Not A Gangster by Bobby Cummines - Books - Random House Books Australia|last=Cummines|first=Bobby|publisher=[[Random House]]|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n| death_date         =